Diagnostics capture happens silently the moment the popup opens (snapshot the ring buffers,
route, device) so it reflects the state before the user started typing.

6. Diagnostic capture mechanics (client runtime)
Implement a small always-on collector mounted high in _app.js (SupportDiagnosticsProvider) that
maintains bounded ring buffers (cheap, capped, never persisted unless a report is filed):

Console errors/warns: monkey-patch console.error/console.warn (preserve originals) → push
to a capped buffer (last ~25). Strip immediately.

Unhandled errors: window.addEventListener('error'|'unhandledrejection') → buffer.

Failed requests: wrap window.fetch (and optionally XHR) to record {method,url,status,ms}
for non-2xx responses only; URL path + scrubbed query. Cap last ~25. No bodies.

Recent actions: subscribe to router.events (route changes) + a lightweight global click
listener that resolves the nearest [data-dev-section-key]/sectionKey ancestor and records a
human label + section key. Cap last ~30.

Device/viewport/session/flags: read on demand at capture time from navigator, window,
useUser(), and the NEXT_PUBLIC_* allowlist.

Code ownership: at capture, resolve the section key under the report trigger (or the most
recently interacted section) and look it up in DEV_LAYOUT_SECTION_SOURCE_MAP to attach
file/line/breadcrumb. Reuse the resolver logic in auditTags.js (buildAuditKey).

Screenshot: prefer DOM-to-image of the app root. Options, in order of preference:

Browser-native navigator.mediaDevices.getDisplayMedia (user picks the tab — most accurate, but
extra click + permission). 2. A lightweight DOM snapshot (no new heavy dep — if html2canvas-class
library is undesirable, capture a serialised DOM + computed styles is overkill; recommend
getDisplayMedia for v1, DOM-rasterise later). Capture client-side; upload as part of submit.
Keep image dimensions/quality capped (e.g. max 1600px wide, JPEG/PNG, < 2 MB) to bound payload.

