8. Repo-change / version tracking (pin reports to exact code state)
So reports stay tied to the exact code state:

Expose build metadata. In next.config.*, set env/publicRuntimeConfig (or
generateBuildId) to surface: NEXT_PUBLIC_COMMIT_SHA = process.env.VERCEL_GIT_COMMIT_SHA,
NEXT_PUBLIC_COMMIT_REF = process.env.VERCEL_GIT_COMMIT_REF, NEXT_PUBLIC_APP_VERSION (from
package.json), and capture Next's buildId. For local dev, fall back to git rev-parse HEAD
at build via the existing tools/scripts pattern.

Stamp every report with app_version, commit_sha, commit_ref, build_id (columns in §3.1).

Code-ownership freshness. DEV_LAYOUT_SECTION_SOURCE_MAP is generated
(generate-dev-layout-section-source-map.js, run on predev/prebuild via the existing
presentation:sync-style hook). Ensure the generator runs in CI/build so source_file/source_line
reflect the committed code at report time. Store the section_key (stable) as the durable
anchor and the resolved file as a convenience snapshot — if files move later, re-resolving by
key against the historical commit gives the correct location.

Optionally store a short content hash of the resolved component file at capture time to detect
drift between report and current code.

9. Error boundaries
Add an app-level error boundary wrapping the page content inside StaffLayout (or in
_app.js), modelled on the existing class boundary in job-cards/[jobNumber].js. On catch it:
(a) renders a friendly fallback ("Something went wrong"), (b) pushes the error+componentStack into
the diagnostics ring buffer, and (c) offers a "Report this problem" button that opens the
support popup pre-filled with the captured error.

Keep the existing job-card boundaries; nest the global one above them.

Boundaries cannot catch event-handler/async errors — those are covered by the
window error listeners in §6.

