Cap file size at the API; reject non-image MIME types.

13. Performance impact
Ring buffers are tiny and capped — negligible memory, no network until a report is filed.

fetch/console patching adds a thin synchronous wrapper; keep it allocation-light and guard with
a feature flag so it can be disabled.

Screenshot is the only heavy op and is user-initiated, off the hot path. Cap resolution/size.

No always-on uploads, no telemetry beaconing. Provider does zero work when idle.

Lazy-load the SupportReportModal (dynamic import) so the popup code isn't in the initial bundle.

14. Testing approach
Use the existing stacks: Vitest (npm run test:unit) for logic, Playwright (npm run test)
for flows.

Unit (Vitest): the sanitiser (§4) — feed payloads containing JWTs, API keys, emails, NI/card
numbers, secret query params, and assert they're redacted; size-cap rejection; section-key →
file resolution against DEV_LAYOUT_SECTION_SOURCE_MAP; build-metadata stamping.

Integration: API routes — auth gating (anon rejected, non-admin can POST but not GET list),
server-side re-sanitisation actually strips secrets even if client sends them, storage upload path.

E2E (Playwright): open "?" → fill form → (mock) screenshot → submit → success toast; admin
logs in → sees report in /dev/support-reports → opens detail → diagnostics present, secrets
absent; non-admin cannot reach the dev viewer; error boundary fallback renders and its "Report"
button pre-fills.

Repo checks: must pass npm run check:borders, npm run check:layers, and npm run uk:check
(UK English) — all new UI obeys the design laws.

Privacy regression test: a dedicated test that submits a report with planted secrets in
console/fetch buffers and asserts the persisted row contains none of them.

15. Phased rollout (implementation order)
Each phase is independently shippable and leaves the app working.

Phase 1 — Foundation & data model
Create support_reports table + indexes (SQL migration following repo convention).

Add src/lib/database/support.js helper (CRUD) and src/lib/support/sanitise.js (with tests).

Create private support-reports storage bucket via ensureBucket.

Exit: can insert/read a sanitised report via helper from a script/test.

Phase 2 — Capture runtime
SupportDiagnosticsProvider in _app.js: ring buffers (console, errors, failed fetch, actions),
device/session/flags snapshot, code-ownership resolver via DEV_LAYOUT_SECTION_SOURCE_MAP.

SupportReportContext with openSupportReport().

Exit: buffers populate; captureDiagnostics() returns a clean, sanitised bundle (unit-tested).

Phase 3 — UI: the "?" control + popup
Add "?" button to StaffTopbar.js right column (wired to context).

SupportReportModal (lazy-loaded) built on PopupModal, modelled on NextActionPrompt; screenshot
capture + preview/redaction; success/error via AlertContext/StatusMessage.

POST /api/support/reports route (createHandler) with server re-sanitise + upload + audit.

Exit: any user can file a report end-to-end; secrets verified absent in DB.

Phase 4 — Error boundaries
App-level error boundary (modelled on the job-card one) feeding the diagnostics buffer and offering
a pre-filled "Report this problem" action.

Exit: a thrown render error shows fallback + can be reported.

Phase 5 — Version / code-state pinning
Surface NEXT_PUBLIC_COMMIT_SHA/_REF/APP_VERSION/buildId via next.config; stamp reports.

Ensure source-map generator runs in build; store section_key + resolved file (+ optional file hash).

Exit: every new report carries commit/version and accurate code ownership.

Phase 6 — Dev viewer, triage & audit
/dev/support-reports list + detail (admin-gated), filters, signed screenshot URLs.

GET/PATCH admin APIs; status/severity/assign/comment; writeAuditLog on every mutation + bundle view.

Exit: admins triage reports; all access/changes audited.

Phase 7 — Hardening
Rate limiting + size caps; retention rule in run-retention.js; RLS review; full Playwright +
privacy regression suite; performance sanity check.

Exit: feature production-ready, documented in docs/.

